"1224","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1180–":"1180–Overleden","1175–Male":"1175–Overleden","1201–Male":"1201–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1180–":"1180–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1201–Male":"1201–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1175":"1175","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name, chiefly from Paston in Norfolk, probably derived from an Old English personal name <i>Pæcci</i> (genitive <i>Pæcces</i>) or Old English <i>pæsc(e)</i> (the source of northern English dialect <i>pash</i> ‘puddle’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","English (West Midlands): sometimes a variant of <b>Patstone</b>, a habitational name chiefly from the lost <i>Padston(e)</i> in Bromsgrove (Worcestershire), and occasionally from Padson in Inwardleigh (Devon). The Worcestershire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Padda</i> (genitive <i>Paddes</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The etymology of the Devon placename is uncertain due to a lack of medieval forms, though an early spelling suggests the final element is Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":110,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Paston was bo